#data into factors
#factor_columns <- names(dat_raw %>% select(-G3, -age, -absences))
factor_columns <- names(dat_raw %>% select(-G3, -age, -absences, -famrel, -traveltime, -studytime, -freetime, -goout, -Walc, -Dalc, -health, -failures, -Medu, -Fedu))

#factorise and log for absences
dat <- dat_raw %>% 
  mutate_at(factor_columns, as.factor) %>%
  mutate(log_absences = log(absences+1)) %>% 
  select(-absences)

#all numeric variables in the dataset
numeric_columns <- names(dat %>% select (G3, age, log_absences, famrel, traveltime, studytime, freetime, goout, Walc, Dalc, health, failures, Medu, Fedu))



#data with numeric varibles
dat_numeric <- dat %>% 
 select(all_of(numeric_columns))

#glimpse(dat_numeric)

Review continious variables

boxplot(scale(dat_numeric))

# Create long data for lm
dat_numeric <- dat_numeric %>% 
  mutate(ID = row_number())

dat_long_vars_no_G3 <- dat_numeric %>%
  select(-G3) %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    !ID,
    names_to = "var",
    values_to = "val"
)

dat_long <- left_join(
  dat_numeric %>% select(ID, G3),
  dat_long_vars_no_G3,
  by = "ID"
) %>% select(-ID)


#check linearity for numerical variables
ggplot(dat_long, aes(x = val, y = G3)) +
  geom_point() + theme_classic(base_size = 12) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~var, ncol = 3, scales = "free_x")

Comparing these models, the Forward model has the least AIC, which means this model is better than others at predicting correct and accurate grade values. However, the adjusted R squared value of the Forward model is smaller than other models. That means this model explains smaller percentages of observed grade values than others. There is trade in between prediction and explaining observer value.

Grade = 8.8447 + (-1.4916) failures + (-1.4524) schoolMS + (1.8356) higheryew + (0.4557) studytime + (-1.2775) schoolsupyes + (-0.3745) Dalc + (-0.1781) health + (-0.4233) Medu1 + (-0.4423) Medu2 + (-0.1690) Medu3 + (0.4483) Medu4 + (0.5346) sexF + (-0.43) romenticyes + (0.1602) age

On average, one unit increase in failure results in a 150% decrease in grade.

On average, if a student is in Mousinho da Silveira (MS), there is a 145% decrease in grade.

On average, if a student wants to take a higher education, there is a 184% increase in grade.

There are 5 levels of study time. In the first level, students study less than 2 hours weekly. For the second level, students study between 2 hours and 5 hours weekly. The third is between 5 and 10 hours and the last one is greater than 10 hours. On average, a level increase in study time results in a 46% increase in grade.

On average, a student taking extra education support could cause a 128% decrease in grade.

On average, one unit increase in workday alcohol consumption results in a 38% decrease in grade.

On average, one unit increase in health results in a 18% decrease in grade.

On average, if the mothers education is 4th grade, students probably get a 42% decrease in grade.

On average, if the mothers education is between 5th and 9th grade, students probably get a 44% decrease in grade.

On average, if the mothers education is secondary education, students probably get a 17% decrease in grade.

On average, if the mothers education is higher than secondary, students probably get a 45% increase in grade.
